result.execSummary:
The defendant Hevenly Breeze Wilson was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Possess w/ Intent/Deliver Non-Narcotics, a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(1m)(b).
  • Resisting or Obstructing an Officer, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 946.41(1).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

supervisions.notes: Defendant eligible for early discharge after 1 year upon Agent's application to the Court.

miscConds.notes: Defendant shall obtain and maintain full time employment or attend school to obtain GED/HSED or its equivalent or a combination of the both.

Defendant shall not possess any illegal substances or drug paraphernalia as defined in Chapter 961.
Defendant shall not operate a motor vehicle on a highway in this State unless authorized to do so by DMV
Defendant's record shall be expunged per Section 973.015 Wis Stats if probation is successfully completed.

Defendant to pay supervision fees as determined by DOC.
Defendant shall submit to any assessments and fully participate in any counseling deemed appropriate by the Agent and abide by any treatment recommendations.
Defendant shall possess prescription medication only by valid prescription and take in the manner and method as prescribed by physician.
Defendant shall maintain absolute sobriety.
Defendant shall receive Alcohol and other Drug Assessment from Waupaca County DHHS or other licensed agency as determined by Agent and abide by any treatment recommendations.
